title: For Trade:  1985 Honda 200X for 1200 rounds of 556 Ammunition
postcontent: I have a 1985 Honda 200X ATC I would like to trade for 1200 rounds of 556 XM855 steel-core ammunition. I would prefer Lake City green-tip, Israeli NATO, or even Winchester steel core, damn near anything except X-TAC!  Like most people, I would prefer a sealed box of ammo rather than loose rounds. I'm now a family man with two daughters to keep safe, and quality rifle ammo is getting very expensive & difficult to find! I still have the original title and instruction manual for the ATC, almost completely unheard of. I have them scanned but they are too large to upload on armslist.  I have taken very good care of this 3-wheeler, and it was packaged accordingly for long term storage! If you're interested in trading an/or have any questions, feel free to send me an email, I'll respond quickly. I will also send you a scanned copy of the Title, Instruction Manual and picture of the 200X.     Justin

I have listed for sale my Ruger Vacquero 5.5" Blued/Case Hardened finish pistol chambered in .45 Colt. Ruger has verified from the serial number that this pistol shipped from the factory in the first month of production of the Vaquero (April, 1993). This is NOT the New Vaquero. This pistol is the original Vaquero that is capable of safely firing the higher pressure "Ruger-only" loads found in the handload manuals. The New Model Vaquero has thinner cylinder walls and cannot accept these loads. What that means is that this Vaquero is capable of loads exceeding .44 magnum balistics.

Condition of this pistol is Very Good to Excellent, though it is a shooter and not a collection piece. The bore is shiny. The pistol has slight wear at the muzzle and end of the ejector housing. The ejector housing also has slight scratches at the bottom, and scratches from the ejector rod cycling and removal of the cylinder. Overall blued finish is 90+%. Slight turn marks on the cylinder. The case hardened finish is more difficult to rate, but appears 80-90+% ( I can't tell if there has been some fading, or if that is the way it came). Disclaimer, I am not an expert at rating firearms, so the condition could be slightly better or worse than I have stated.

There is no box or paperwork with this pistol. As well, the grips are not original, as it shipped from the factory with eagle rosewood grips (which I do not have).

I have done my research online as best I could and found pistols of this vintage and condition to go from $600-$700, the higher end are with box and no papers. Pistol will come with a box of Hornady Critical Defense.

title: For Sale:  Freedom Munitions 9mm 115 gr. RN Box of 650 Will to split 2 times
location: Southwest 115 and Academy, Colorado Springs, Colorado
postcontent:
FREEDOM MUNITIONS inspects all cartridge cases for defects. The Scharch Range Master machines are fully automated and cases are checked for any debris and pressure tested for any splits or cracks. Primers are removed, flash holes are cleared, and primer pockets are reamed to accept new primers.

FREEDOM MUNITIONS then washes cases in an acid wash specially designed to remove all remaining burnt powder from the flash hole and interior of the case which tumbling doesn't remove. Then cases are tumbled in a dryer for a factory look and finish.

FREEDOM MUNITIONS roll sizes all cases on our own designed machines to meet S.A.A.M.I.specification. This method is the industry standard for commercial sizing, insuring the case wall is sized down to the rim which insures new component performance.

FREEDOM MUNITIONS then loads these processed components on the same fiber optic-controlled Ammo Load machines as our premium new ammo. These are the same machines used by some of the largest manufacturers in the industry. These machines assure S.A.A.M.I. specifications for priming depth, pressure and overall cartridge length.

FREEDOM MUNITIONS "Like-New" manufacturing process with the new projectile, powder and primer assures factory ammo performance that discriminating shooters expect.
